<DOC><DOCNO> AP891220-0251 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-20-89 0156EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-IBM     12-20 0247</FIRST><SECOND>PM-IBM,0255</SECOND><HEAD>IBM Announces Agreement With Software Company, New PC Model</HEAD><DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   International Business Machines Corp.has announced a partnership with a small software company that willallow IBM's OfficeVision software to connect with office softwaresystems of other manufacturers.   Under the agreement, Soft-Switch, of Wayne, Pa., has designedsoftware that will allow companies using OfficeVision to exchangecomputer documents and electronic mail with office systems made byDigital Equipment Corp., Wang Laboratories Inc., Hewlett-PackardCo. and others, IBM said Tuesday.   OfficeVision, introduced by IBM in May, allows companies usingvarious IBM computers of different sizes to tie them together inone system. The software overcomes the incompatibility of many IBMproducts, a shortfall that has been exploited by Digital and othercompanies that make only compatible machines.   The Soft-Switch products will be sold by both IBM andSoft-Switch. They will be available Dec. 29 and will be priced from$40,000 to $250,000, IBM said.   Separately Tuesday, IBM introduced the most powerful member ofits Personal System-2 computer family, a model based on IntelCorp.'s i486 microprocessor. The model, called the PS-2 Model 70486, is priced at $12,395 and up.   In addition, IBM said it would resume shipping a kit to upgradeits earlier PS-2 Model 70 computers by adding the i486 chip. IBMstopped shipping the kits in October after Intel alerted it to aflaw in the chips. The trouble was corrected with a new version ofthe microprocessor.</TEXT></DOC>